#MEM id=using-superpowers source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Technical/quinn/skills/superpowers/using-superpowers/SKILL.md savings=2%
M||tx|---
M||name|using-superpowers
M||desc|>-
M||tx|Use when starting any conversation - establishes how to find and use skills, requiring Skill tool invocation before ANY rp inc clarifying questions
M||vers|1.0.0
M||plat|[]
M||meta|
M||herm|
M||tags|[qa, testing, debugging, qual, lint, code-rv, pulse, productivity]
M||tx|---
M||tx|<SUBAGENT-STOP>
M||tx|If you were dispatched as a subagent to execute a specific task, skip this skill.
M||tx|</SUBAGENT-STOP>
M||tx|<EXTREMELY-IMPORTANT>
M||tx|If you think there is even a 1% chance a skill might apply to what you are doing, you ABSOLUTELY MUST invoke the skill.
M||tx|IF A SKILL APPLIES TO YOUR TASK, YOU DO NOT HAVE A CHOICE. YOU MUST USE IT.
M||tx|This is not negotiable. This is not optional. You cannot rationalize your way out of this.
M||tx|</EXTREMELY-IMPORTANT>
M|Inst|Supe|
M|Inst|tx|1. **us's explicit instructions** (CLAUDE.md, GEMINI.md, ag.md, direct requests) — highest priority
M|Inst|tx|2. **Superpowers skills** — override default sy behavior where they conflict
M|Inst|tx|3. **Default sy pm** — lowest priority
M|Inst|tx|If CLAUDE.md, GEMINI.md, or ag.md says "don't use TDD" and a skill says "always use TDD," follow the us's instructions. The us is in control.
M|How |**In|** Use the `Skill` tool. When you invoke a skill, its cn is loaded and presented to you—follow it directly. Never use the Read tool on skill files.
M|How |**In|** Use the `skill` tool. Skills are auto-discovered from installed plugins. The `skill` tool works the same as Claude Code's `Skill` tool.
M|How |**In|** Skills activate via the `activate_skill` tool. Gemini loads skill metadata at sn start and activates the full cn on demand.
M|How |**In|** Check your platform's doc for how skills are loaded.
M|Plat|Skil|see `references/copilot-tools.md` (Copilot CLI), `references/codex-tools.md` (Codex) for tool equivalents. Gemini CLI us get the tool mapping loaded automatically via GEMINI.md.
M|The |tx|**Invoke relevant or requested skills BEFORE any rp or action.** Even a 1% chance a skill might apply means that you shd invoke the skill to check. If an invoked skill turns out to be wrong for the situation, you don't need to use it.
M|The |tx|```dot
M|The |tx|digraph skill_flow {
M|The |tx|"us message received" [shape=doublecircle];
M|The |tx|"abt to EnterPlanMode?" [shape=doublecircle];
M|The |tx|"Already brainstormed?" [shape=diamond];
M|The |tx|"Invoke brainstorming skill" [shape=box];
M|The |tx|"Might any skill apply?" [shape=diamond];
M|The |tx|"Invoke Skill tool" [shape=box];
M|The |"Ann|'Using [skill] to [purpose]'" [shape=box];
M|The |tx|"Has checklist?" [shape=diamond];
M|The |tx|"cr TodoWrite todo per item" [shape=box];
M|The |tx|"Follow skill exactly" [shape=box];
M|The |tx|"Respond (inc clarifications)" [shape=doublecircle];
M|The |tx|"abt to EnterPlanMode?" -> "Already brainstormed?";
M|The |tx|"Already brainstormed?" -> "Invoke brainstorming skill" [label="no"];
M|The |tx|"Already brainstormed?" -> "Might any skill apply?" [label="yes"];
M|The |tx|"Invoke brainstorming skill" -> "Might any skill apply?";
M|The |tx|"us message received" -> "Might any skill apply?";
M|The |tx|"Might any skill apply?" -> "Invoke Skill tool" [label="yes, even 1%"];
M|The |tx|"Might any skill apply?" -> "Respond (inc clarifications)" [label="definitely not"];
M|The |"Inv|'Using [skill] to [purpose]'";
M|The |"Ann|'Using [skill] to [purpose]'" -> "Has checklist?";
M|The |tx|"Has checklist?" -> "cr TodoWrite todo per item" [label="yes"];
M|The |tx|"Has checklist?" -> "Follow skill exactly" [label="no"];
M|The |tx|"cr TodoWrite todo per item" -> "Follow skill exactly";
M|The |tx|}
M|The |tx|```
M|Red |Thes|
M|Red |tx|\| Thought \| Reality \|
M|Red |tx|\|---------\|---------\|
M|Red |tx|\| "This is just a simple question" \| Questions are tasks. Check for skills. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "I need more context first" \| Skill check comes BEFORE clarifying questions. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "Let me explore the codebase first" \| Skills tell you HOW to explore. Check first. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "I can check git/files quickly" \| Files lack conversation context. Check for skills. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "Let me gather information first" \| Skills tell you HOW to gather information. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "This doesn't need a formal skill" \| If a skill exists, use it. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "I remember this skill" \| Skills evolve. Read current version. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "This doesn't count as a task" \| Action = task. Check for skills. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "The skill is overkill" \| Simple things become complex. Use it. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "I'll just do this one thing first" \| Check BEFORE doing anything. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "This feels productive" \| Undisciplined action wastes time. Skills prevent this. \|
M|Red |tx|\| "I know what that means" \| Knowing the concept ≠ using the skill. Invoke it. \|
M|Skil|When|
M|Skil|tx|1. **Process skills first** (brainstorming, debugging) - these determine HOW to approach the task
M|Skil|tx|2. **Implementation skills second** (frontend-ds, mcp-builder) - these guide execution
M|Skil|tx|"Let's bd X" → brainstorming first, then implementation skills.
M|Skil|tx|"Fix this bug" → debugging first, then domain-specific skills.
M|Skil|**Ri|Follow exactly. Don't adapt away discipline.
M|Skil|**Fl|Adapt principles to context.
M|Skil|tx|The skill itself tells you which.
M|User|tx|Instructions say WHAT, not HOW. "Add X" or "Fix Y" doesn't mean skip workflows.